709017f-a.title: Manhattan: 5th Avenue - 56th Street
709017f-a.text:
5h Ave., e.5., & 56h St.
A front view of New York's most beautiful and perfectly app0inted home for the apparel of women, a1sSes and children, the Bonait Ieller shop at Fifth Ave. & 56h St. In taking over what was formerly the Stewart Building, Bonwit eller found it necessary to completely reconstruct both its interior E exterior plan to fit the physical necessities of their organization and to meet their policies and ideals. Ely Jacques Kahn is the architect responsible for this reconstruction. Shown here is a section of the new front of the store with its dignified facade of Benedict metsl and glass which runs up two floors and enables the shop to be flooded with sunlight.
Sigurd Tischer, photographer.  79a2

713810f-a.title: Manhattan: 56th Street (West) - 5th Avenue
713810f-a.text:
West 56th Street, north side, west from (No. 29), a point midway between Fifth and Sixth Aves., and to the latter (left), showing: the Arthur Lehman (No. 31), the W. H. Donahue (No. 33, entrance canopy), the George A. Helme (No. 35, occupied at one time by Thomas Alva Edison), the R. Wanamaker (No. 37), the Annie K. Smith (Ne. 39), eto., residences. The majority of these structures have been given over to commercial enterprises, prominent of which was a dinner dance club, the "Place Elegante" in the former Donahue home. For an account of the latter see
the New York Daily News of October 1, 1937 (columnist).
